One in four views the pill as very unacceptable (26 percent), which is significantly higher than the proportion in southern European welfare states. However, there is no evidence of changing opinions on abortion, since these attitudes have been relatively stable since independence (ICLS, 2011; ICIBH, 2014). During the European financial crisis, the courts in some countries saw an increase of at least 50 percent in applications by women requesting exemptions from school fees (Berliner & Surbey, 2015).
Around 56 percent of Turkish citizens across the surveyed Mediterranean countries believe it is difficult to avoid unwanted pregnancies. This is a high level that does not appear to respond to policies in force. Regardless of the fact that there are stronger antiunwanted pregnancy stances in turkey in comparison to Southern European countries, with 78 percent of Turkish citizens dissenting this notion and trusting in availability of effective pregnancy prevention methods, when women hold the problematic view, only 29 percent think that it is difficult to avoid an unwanted pregnancy.
